Package me.wobblyyyy.edt

Class DynamicMap<K,​V>

  • java.lang.Object
    • me.wobblyyyy.edt.DynamicMap<K,​V>
  • Type Parameters:
    K - the type used for key elements.
    V - the type used for value elements.
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    Mappable<K,​V>
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    IntegerMap, StringMap
    public class DynamicMap<K,​V>
extends java.lang.Object
implements Mappable<K,​V>
    A re-implementation of the map concept, designed to leverage a pair of linked DynamicArray instances to improve performance.

    It's very important to note that many of the performance improvements you see from using a DynamicMap over something like a HashMap come from smaller-sized maps. HashMap elements are very effective at storing thousands upon thousands of entries. DynamicMap elements, unlike HashMap elements, store entries in a pair of linked arrays instead of a hash table.

    DynamicMap elements are faster than the similar HashMap data structure. Well, in some situations. Specifically:

    • Adding elements to the map. DynamicMap elements are nearly four times faster than comparable HashMap elements.
    • Removing elements from the map. Like adding elements, removing elements with a DynamicArray is nearly four times faster than doing the same on a HashMap.

    One of the biggest improvements the DynamicMap class provides over the HashMap class (or other similar maps) is the speed of iteration. Especially over larger data sets. Although lookup times on the dynamic map are rather high, in large part due to index calculations, iteration speeds are typically half of that in a comparable hash map. In a simple test of a map (size 100,000), dynamic maps scored an average of 14,213 NS compared to hash map's 60,000 NS. Obviously, this is a huge improvement. These drastic differences in execution time carry over to smaller maps as well. If you're planning on iterating over your data very frequently, using a dynamic map over another type of map might be a good idea.

    Author:
    Colin Robertson

      • DynamicMap

        public DynamicMap​(int minSize)
        Create a new DynamicMap without any elements. Because the map doesn't have any elements, you'll have to add some later.
        Parameters:
        minSize - the minimum size to be allocated by the internal dynamic arrays. Having a larger minimum size decreases the amount of time that will need to be spent on memory allocation in the future. Using a larger maximum size will, however, use more memory. The minimum size should generally be the average amount of entries your map will have. By default, this value is 10.

      • DynamicMap

        public DynamicMap​(KeyValue<K,​V>[] values)
        Create a new DynamicMap, using an array of key-value pairs of the type K, V.
        Parameters:
        values - an array of keys and values to add to the map upon construction. Each of these values will be added to the map as soon as it's created. The minimum size of the map will be set to the length of the values array.

      • DynamicMap

        public DynamicMap​(java.util.Map<K,​V> inputMap)
        Create a new DynamicMap using a map as a base. The elements in this map will be converted to the dynamic map. Note that this conversion can take a while, as it requires map iteration, which isn't exactly blazing fast, especially on certain implementations of the map interface. But it works!
        Parameters:
        inputMap - the map that the DynamicMap's values should be set to/cloned to.

    • Method Detail

      • put

        public void put​(K key,
                V value)
        Put a given pair into the map. If the map already contains an element with the same key as the key that was inputted, replace that key's value. If the map doesn't contain the given key and the map can be expanded to include it, insert the value into the map.

        This method operates by attempting to determine the index of the requested key. If the index of that key is -1, the key isn't contained in the map - we now respond by adding the input key/value pair to the map's internal arrays. If the index of that requested key is anything above -1 (non-inclusive) then the key already is included in the map's set, and we can simply over-write that key's value.

        Specified by:
        put in interface Mappable<K,​V>
        Parameters:
        key - the key that the value should go under.
        value - the value the key should have.
        See Also:
        Mappable.put(KeyValue)

        public void add​(K key,

        Add a key-value pair to the map. Adding doesn't mean setting - it really does mean adding a key-value pair. If there is already the given key contained in the array, another instance of that key will be added, in addition to the value.

        If you want to set/put an element, you can use either the set or put methods provided in the DynamicMap class.

        Parameters:

        value - the value's... well, the value's value.

      • getKeys

        public DynamicArray<K> getKeys()
        Get a DynamicArray of key elements stored internally.

        PLEASE NOTE! You shouldn't ever modify the value of this array directly. You should almost always use the methods provided in the dynamic map class to modify these values. You can look at these values, or use any of the methods from the DynamicArray class that you'd like to, but it is very strongly suggested that you don't modify them.

        Modifying these values may de-couple the linked arrays that compose this type of map, thus defeating the entire purpose of the map.

        Specified by:

        a DynamicArray of elements.

        public int size()

        Although it probably doesn't matter from an API perspective, it's worth noting that this method determines the size of the map by getting the size of the internal keys array. Unless external modification happens to these arrays (without the help of methods provided in this class) this size value should always be accurate.

      • realSize

        public int realSize()
        Get the "real" size of the map.

        This "real" size represents the combined allocated length of both of the internally-used arrays. Generally, you should use size - NOT real size, as this might not be the size you're expecting.

        Returns:
        the "real" size of the keys array plus the "real" size of the values array.

      • trim

        public void trim()
        Trim the active portion of the dynamic map. This method acts to free up memory. It's suggested that you call this method after adding a great number of elements to the map and then removing them. The larger the map is, the more memory needs to be allocated to the map. Trimming the map will force the re-allocation of the internal arrays, thus reducing the map's memory footprint.

        To cite the documentation provided in the DynamicArray class:

        Array elements aren't always wiped from the array whenever that element is removed. In order to optimize performance, these values are often left alone until they're no longer needed. However, if you would like to cut down on memory usage, using this method will allow you to reduce the memory footprint of the DynamicArray by trimming any values that aren't actively being used by the array.

        See Also:
        DynamicArray.trim()

      • clear

        public void clear()
        Clear all of the values contained in the active portion of the map.

        It's important to note that this method WILL NOT re-size the map. The active portion of the DynamicMap will still be whatever it was before. This method will, however, set all of the elements in the active portion of the map to be equal to null.

        Specified by:
        clear in interface Mappable<K,​V>
        See Also:
        reset()

      • reset

        public void reset()
        Reset the entire DynamicMap. Resetting the map clears all of the values in the map, resets the map's size to the defined minimum size, and trims the internal array.

        Resetting a map is the optimal way to totally wipe the map without having to create another map. If you'd just like to wipe the map's values, you can use the clear() method. If you'd like to resize the map to make it as small as possible, you can use the trim() method. If you'd like to get a fresh start, this method right here is your guy.
